							<p>St Therese Chinese Catholic Church, originally known as Santa Maria Incoronata, serves the spiritual needs of some within the Chinatown community. Santa Maria Incoronata had its first baptism when the parish was officially founded on November 26th, 1899. However, it wasn’t until December 8th, 1903 that the parish held its first mass. <br>
									<i>This is because, according to the church’s priest,</i> "At the beginning the church was for the Italians, because the proportion of Chinese in this area was very low, and most of the residents were Italian. And the number of Chinese catholic was also really small."<br>
									On April 14th, 1904, the cornerstone of Santa Maria Incoronata was laid and the church was officially open. In September of 1914, the Santa Maria Catholic school was opened. During this time period, Al Capone’s mother donated a large crucifix, which still hangs in the church. <br>
									On April 8th, 1946, the parish dedicated the Chapel of St. Therese Chinese Mission. It wasn’t until October 18th, 1947 that the St Therese Chinese Mission was formally erected as a Chinese Catholic community. The community celebrated its first Chinese Mass at the Santa Maria Incoronata Parish. <br>
									About 30 years later, due to the influx of Chinese immigrants to the city of Chicago, there became a need to serve more Chinese Catholics who now found themselves living in America. As such, with a large enough population, the first Chinese Catholic Church Opened on September 11th, 2014. Roughly a year later, the St Therese school opened its doors for classes. Nine months later, St Therese school handed out it’s first diplomas. According to the church’s priest:<br>
									<i>“The church will worship Chinese traditional ancestors during the Spring Festival every year and offer sacrifices. At this time, not only the Catholic Church will come to participate in this activity, but many other organizations will also come.” </i> <br> 
									The most drastic change for the Chinese Catholic Community occured in 1963, when the Church of Santa Maria Incoronata was passed on to the St Therese Chinese Mission. From then on, the church was run by the Chinese Catholic Community. In 2001, the church made major renovations in order to re-beautify the church. Chinese symbols and newly imported furniture was added. In 2011, St Therese Catholic School was officially dedicated as a National Blue Ribbon School.</p>
